<LP>
   MANUFACTURING GREW in April for the first time in 11
months, purchasing managers said. But construction spending
fell 1.4% in March, the first decline this year. Both
manufacturing and construction have been hurt by the Fed's
efforts to battle inflation with high rates.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stocks edged higher in reaction to the purchasing
managers' report, while bond prices weakened. The Dow Jones
industrials closed up 12.16, at 2668.92. The dollar drifted
lower.
   ---
   Chrysler posted a $71 million profit for the first
quarter, surpassing expectations and pushing its stock up 75
cents, to $15.25. Though earnings were down 80% from a year
earlier, the auto maker was expected to only break even due
to sharply lower production and slumping sales.
   ---
   Coca-Cola scored a major coup against Pepsi-Cola by
swiping its biggest fountain client, Burger King. Coke
already supplies the nation's largest fast-food chain,
McDonald's.
   ---
   The House approved a $1.24 trillion spending plan for
fiscal 1991 that Democrats viewed as little more than their
opening position for talks with the Senate and White House.
   ---
   Mitsubishi Motors agreed to buy a majority stake in Value
Rent-a-Car, becoming the first Japanese maker to align itself
with a U.S. car-rental firm. Terms weren't disclosed.
   ---
   American General is likely to remain under pressure to
find a buyer or take other action to boost its stock price
whether or not hostile suitor Torchmark wins today's proxy
vote. The vote is expected to be close.
   ---
   Georgia-Pacific said it is considering selling some assets
to help pay off debt from its recent $3.74 billion
acquisition of Great Northern Nekoosa.
   ---
   Michael Milken will be subpoenaed by a House panel, which
agreed to offer immunity to the former junk-bond king in
return for his testimony. A hearing could be held this
summer.
   ---
   Carl Icahn isn't expected to win his proxy battle to split
USX into separate steel and energy businesses. But he is
forcing the company's management to consider some bold
initiatives.
   ---
   The S&amp;L bailout's rising cost is causing concern at the
White House, which said it is starting to seek a new FDIC
chief to handle the problem.
   ---
   OPEC ministers arrived in Geneva for today's start of an
emergency meeting, apparently convinced that short-term
production cuts are the only way to calm the oil markets.
                                                                                                       

   Gasoline prices aren't expected to decline anytime soon
despite the recent 20% slide in crude-oil prices.
   ---
   The American Stock Exchange is seeking SEC permission to
list U.S. stock-index warrants that would let investors bet
on the market's direction over the next three years.
   ---
   The New York state sales tax may soon be broadly expanded
to cover such services as custom computer programming,
management consulting and public relations.
   ---
   Group of Seven officials plan to meet in Washington Sunday
to resolve issues that are holding up a proposed capital
increase for the IMF.
   ---
   Legislation to stiffen penalties for workplace-safety
violations was endorsed by the Bush administration.
   ---
